Healthcare workers form part of an essential service, and therefore have to continue fighting the good fight while others stay at home. #21daylockdownSA #DStv403 GENEVA - As COVID-19 captures global headlines, the World Health Organization (WHO) warned that the world needs nearly six million nurses. The UN's health agency along with partners Nursing Now and the International Council of Nurses (ICN) underscored in a report the crucial role played by nurses, who make up more than half of all health workers worldwide. READ: Denosa calls for greater protection of nurses "Nurses are the backbone of any health system," WHO chief Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said in a statement. "Today, many nurses find themselves on the frontline in the battle against COVID-19," he noted, adding that it was vital they "get the support they need to keep the world healthy." READ: Zimbabwe doctors join nurses on strike over lack of virus protection The report said that there are just under 28 million nurses on the planet. In the five years leading up to 2018, the number grew by 4.7 million. WATCH: Thousands of nurses remain unemployed "But this still leaves a global shortfall of 5.9 million," the WHO said, pointing out that the greatest gaps were in poorer countries in Africa, southeast Asia, the Middle East and parts of South America. The report urged countries to identify gaps in their nursing workforce and invest in nursing education, jobs and leadership.